unitsize(0.6 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (1,0);
B = (4,3);
C = (3,4);
D = (3,0);

real func (real x) {
  return(-x^2 + 6*x - 5);
}

draw(graph(func,0.5,5.5));
draw((-0.5,0)--(5.5,0));
draw((0,-1)--(0,5));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(C--D);

label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, N);
label("$D$", D, S);
[/asy]

Then
\[\frac{1}{2} \cdot AD \cdot CD = \frac{1}{2} \cdot AC \cdot BC \cdot \sin \angle ACB,\]so
\[AD \cdot CD = AC \cdot BC \cdot \sin \angle ACB.\]Since $\sin \angle ACB \le 1,$
\[AD \cdot CD \le AC \cdot BC.\]Hence,
\[\frac{1}{2} (p - 1) q \le \frac{1}{2} \sqrt{(p - 1)^2 + q^2} \cdot \sqrt{(p - 4)^2 + (q - 3)^2}.\]Squaring both sides, we get
\[(p - 1)^2 q^2 \le [(p - 1)^2 + q^2][(p - 4)^2 + (q - 3)^2].\]Expanding, we get
\[0 \le (p - 1)^2 (q - 3)^2 + q^2 (p - 4)^2.\]This inequality holds, since $(p - 1)^2 (q - 3)^2$ and $q^2 (p - 4)^2$ are both nonnegative.

Equality occurs when $p = 1$ and $q = 3,$ so the largest possible area of triangle $ABC$ is
\[\frac{1}{2} \cdot (1 - 1) \cdot 3 = \boxed{0}.\]I hope it is correct.

